To find the inverse of a 2x2 matrix A = \begin{bmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{bmatrix}, we can use the formula:

A⁻¹ = \frac{1}{ad - bc} \begin{bmatrix} d & -b \\ -c & a \end{bmatrix}

In this case, A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 \\ 3 & 4 \end{bmatrix}, so a = 1, b = 2, c = 3, and d = 4.

First, we need to find the determinant (ad - bc):

Determinant = (1 * 4) - (2 * 3) = 4 - 6 = -2

Now, we can find the inverse using the formula:

A⁻¹ = \frac{1}{-2} \begin{bmatrix} 4 & -2 \\ -3 & 1 \end{bmatrix}

A⁻¹ = \begin{bmatrix} -2 & 1 \\ 1.5 & -0.5 \end{bmatrix}

So, the inverse of the matrix A is:

A⁻¹ = \begin{bmatrix} -2 & 1 \\ 1.5 & -0.5 \end{bmatrix}
